from another tribe trapped in a world where she will always be the outsider. Barbara Fass Leavy believes that, in the societies in which the tale and its variants endured, woman was the other--the outsider trapped in a society that could never be her own. Leavy shows how the tale, though rarely explicitly recognized, is frequently replayed in modern literature. Beautifully written, this book reveals the myriad ways in which the folktales of a society reflect its cultural values, and particularly how folktales are allegories of gender relations. It will interest anyone involved in literary, gender, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMan-woman relationshipsvFolklore. 0aMan-woman relationships. 0aSexvFolklore. 0aSex. 0aSwan maiden (Tale)vClassification. 0aSwan maiden (Tale)xHistory and criticism. 0aSwan maiden (Tale). 0aWomenvFolklore. 0aWomen. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081475068140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814752685.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814752685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814752685/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK